# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aminohippuric-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The three dimensional structures of many extracellular proteins, such as the plasma proteins and membrane proteins of the body's cells, are very sensitive to the extracellular pH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Stringent mechanisms therefore exist to maintain the pH within very narrow limits.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Outside the acceptable range of pH, proteins are denatured (i.e. their 3D structure is disrupted), causing enzymes and ion channels (among others) to malfunction.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] An acid–base imbalance is known as acidemia when the pH is acidic, or alkalemia when the pH is alkaline.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Respiratory component: The second line of defense is rapid consisting of the control the carbonic acid (H2CO3) concentration in the ECF by changing the rate and depth of breathing by hyperventilation or hypoventilation.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] This blows off or retains carbon dioxide (and thus carbonic acid) in the blood plasma as required.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Metabolic component: The third line of defense is slow, best measured by the base excess, and mostly depends on the renal system which can add or remove bicarbonate ions (HCO− 3) to or from the ECF.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Bicarbonate ions are derived from metabolic carbon dioxide which is enzymatically converted to carbonic acid in the renal tubular cells.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] There, carbonic acid spontaneously dissociates into hydrogen ions and bicarbonate ions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] When the pH in the ECF falls, hydrogen ions are excreted into urine, while bicarbonate ions are secreted into blood plasma, causing the plasma pH to rise.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The converse happens if the pH in the ECF tends to rise: bicarbonate ions are then excreted into the urine and hydrogen ions into the blood plasma.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The second and third lines of defense operate by making changes to the buffers, each of which consists of two components: a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] It is the ratio concentration of the weak acid to its conjugate base that determines the pH of the solution.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Thus, by manipulating firstly the concentration of the weak acid, and secondly that of its conjugate base, the pH of the extracellular fluid (ECF) can be adjusted very accurately to the correct value.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The bicarbonate buffer, consisting of a mixture of carbonic acid (H2CO3) and a bicarbonate (HCO− 3) salt in solution, is the most abundant buffer in the extracellular fluid, and it is also the buffer whose acid-to-base ratio can be changed very easily and rapidly.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The pH of the extracellular fluid, including the blood plasma, is normally tightly regulated between 7.32 and 7.42 by the chemical buffers, the respiratory system, and the renal system.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The normal pH in the fetus differs from that in the adult.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] In the fetus, the pH in the umbilical vein pH is normally 7.25 to 7.45 and that in the umbilical artery is normally 7.18 to 7.38.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Aqueous buffer solutions will react with strong acids or strong bases by absorbing excess H+ ions, or OH− ions, replacing the strong acids and bases with weak acids and weak bases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] This has the effect of damping the effect of pH changes, or reducing the pH change that would otherwise have occurred.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] But buffers cannot correct abnormal pH levels in a solution, be that solution in a test tube or in the extracellular fluid.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Buffers typically consist of a pair of compounds in solution, one of which is a weak acid and the other a weak base.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The most abundant buffer in the ECF consists of a solution of carbonic acid (H2CO3), and the bicarbonate (HCO− 3) salt of, usually, sodium (Na+).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Thus, when there is an excess of OH− ions in the solution carbonic acid *partially* neutralizes them by forming H2O and bicarbonate (HCO− 3) ions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The pH of a buffer solution depends solely on the *ratio* of the molar concentrations of the weak acid to the weak base.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The higher the concentration of the weak acid in the solution (compared to the weak base) the lower the resulting pH of the solution.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Similarly, if the weak base predominates the higher the resulting pH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] This principle is exploited to *regulate* the pH of the extracellular fluids (rather than just *buffering* the pH).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] For the carbonic acid-bicarbonate buffer, a molar ratio of weak acid to weak base of 1:20 produces a pH of 7.4; and vice versa—when the pH of the extracellular fluids is 7.4 then the ratio of carbonic acid to bicarbonate ions in that fluid is 1:20.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The pH of the extracellular fluids can thus be controlled by the regulation of $P_{{\mathrm {CO} }_{2}}$ and the other metabolic acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Homeostatic control can change the *P*CO2 and hence the pH of the arterial plasma within a few seconds.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the arterial blood is monitored by the central chemoreceptors of the medulla oblongata.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] These chemoreceptors are sensitive to the levels of carbon dioxide and pH in the cerebrospinal fluid.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The central chemoreceptors send their information to the respiratory centers in the medulla oblongata and pons of the brainstem.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The respiratory centres then determine the average rate of ventilation of the alveoli of the lungs, to keep the *P*CO2 in the arterial blood constant.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The respiratory center does so via motor neurons which activate the muscles of respiration (in particular, the diaphragm).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] A rise in the *P*CO2 in the arterial blood plasma above 5.3 kPa (40 mmHg) reflexly causes an increase in the rate and depth of breathing.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Normal breathing is resumed when the partial pressure of carbon dioxide has returned to 5.3 kPa.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The converse happens if the partial pressure of carbon dioxide falls below the normal range.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Breathing may be temporally halted, or slowed down to allow carbon dioxide to accumulate once more in the lungs and arterial blood.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The sensor for the plasma HCO− 3 concentration is not known for certain.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] It is very probable that the renal tubular cells of the distal convoluted tubules are themselves sensitive to the pH of the plasma.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The metabolism of these cells produces CO2, which is rapidly converted to H+ and HCO− 3 through the action of carbonic anhydrase.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] When the extracellular fluids tend towards acidity, the renal tubular cells secrete the H+ ions into the tubular fluid from where they exit the body via the urine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The HCO− 3 ions are simultaneously secreted into the blood plasma, thus raising the bicarbonate ion concentration in the plasma, lowering the carbonic acid/bicarbonate ion ratio, and consequently raising the pH of the plasma.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] The converse happens when the plasma pH rises above normal: bicarbonate ions are excreted into the urine, and hydrogen ions into the plasma.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] These combine with the bicarbonate ions in the plasma to form carbonic acid (H+ + HCO− 3 $\rightleftharpoons$ H2CO3), thus raising the carbonic acid:bicarbonate ratio in the extracellular fluids, and returning its pH to normal.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] In general, metabolism produces more waste acids than bases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Urine produced is generally acidic and is partially neutralized by the ammonia (NH3) that is excreted into the urine when glutamate and glutamine (carriers of excess, no longer needed, amino groups) are deaminated by the distal renal tubular epithelial cells.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Thus some of the "acid content" of the urine resides in the resulting ammonium ion (NH4+) content of the urine, though this has no effect on pH homeostasis of the extracellular fluids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] Acid–base imbalance occurs when a significant insult causes the blood pH to shift out of the normal range (7.32 to 7.42).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/acid-base-homeostasis] An abnormally low pH in the extracellular fluid is called an *acidemia* and an abnormally high pH is called an *alkalemia*.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone is part of the renin–angiotensin–aldosterone system.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] It has a plasma half-life of less than 20 minutes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Drugs that interfere with the secretion or action of aldosterone are in use as antihypertensives, like lisinopril, which lowers blood pressure by blocking the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE), leading to lower aldosterone secretion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The net effect of these drugs is to reduce sodium and water retention but increase the retention of potassium.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] In other words, these drugs stimulate the excretion of sodium and water in urine, while they block the excretion of potassium.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Another example is spironolactone, a potassium-sparing diuretic of the steroidal spirolactone group, which interferes with the aldosterone receptor (among others) leading to lower blood pressure by the mechanism described above.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone was first isolated by Sylvia Tait (Simpson) and Jim Tait in 1953; in collaboration with Tadeusz Reichstein.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The corticosteroids are synthesized from cholesterol within the zona glomerulosa and zona fasciculata of adrenal cortex.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Most steroidogenic reactions are catalysed by enzymes of the cytochrome P450 family.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] They are located within the mitochondria and require adrenodoxin as a cofactor (except 21-hydroxylase and 17α-hydroxylase).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone and corticosterone share the first part of their biosynthetic pathways.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The last parts are mediated either by the aldosterone synthase (for aldosterone) or by the 11β-hydroxylase (for corticosterone).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] These enzymes are nearly identical (they share 11β-hydroxylation and 18-hydroxylation functions), but aldosterone synthase is also able to perform an 18-oxidation.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Moreover, aldosterone synthase is found within the zona glomerulosa at the outer edge of the adrenal cortex; 11β-hydroxylase is found in the zona glomerulosa and zona fasciculata.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone synthase is normally absent in other sections of the adrenal gland.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The secretion of aldosterone has a diurnal rhythm.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone is the primary of several endogenous members of the class of mineralocorticoids in humans.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Deoxycorticosterone is another important member of this class.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone upregulates epithelial sodium channels (ENaCs) in the collecting duct and the colon, increasing apical membrane permeability for Na+ and thus absorption.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Cl− is reabsorbed in conjunction with sodium cations to maintain the system's electrochemical balance.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone stimulates the secretion of K+ into the tubular lumen.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone stimulates Na+ and water reabsorption from the gut, salivary and sweat glands in exchange for K+.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone upregulates expression of NCC in the distal convoluted tubule chronically and its activity acutely.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone is responsible for the reabsorption of about 2% of filtered sodium in the kidneys, which is nearly equal to the entire sodium content in human blood under normal glomerular filtration rates.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone, probably acting through mineralocorticoid receptors, may positively influence neurogenesis in the dentate gyrus.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Steroid receptors are intracellular since steroid hormones are able to cross the cell membrane without a specific transporter.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The aldosterone mineralocorticoid receptor (MR) complex binds on the DNA to specific hormone response element, which leads to gene specific transcription.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Some of the transcribed genes are crucial for transepithelial sodium transport, including the three subunits of the epithelial sodium channel (ENaC), the Na+/K+ pumps and their regulatory proteins serum and glucocorticoid-induced kinase, and channel-inducing factor, respectively.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The MR is stimulated by both aldosterone and cortisol, but a mechanism protects the body from excess aldosterone receptor stimulation by glucocorticoids (such as cortisol), which happen to be present at much higher concentrations than mineralocorticoids in the healthy individual.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The mechanism consists of an enzyme called 11β-Hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (11β-HSD).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] This enzyme co-localizes with intracellular adrenal steroid receptors and converts cortisol into cortisone, a relatively inactive metabolite with little affinity for the MR.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Liquorice, which contains glycyrrhetinic acid, can inhibit 11β-HSD and lead to a mineralocorticoid excess syndrome.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Angiotensin is involved in regulating aldosterone and is the core regulation.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Angiotensin II acts synergistically with potassium, and the potassium feedback is virtually inoperative when no angiotensin II is present.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] A small portion of the regulation resulting from angiotensin II must take place indirectly from decreased blood flow through the liver due to constriction of capillaries.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] When the blood flow decreases so does the destruction of aldosterone by liver enzymes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Although sustained production of aldosterone requires persistent calcium entry through low-voltage-activated Ca2+ channels, isolated zona glomerulosa cells are considered nonexcitable, with recorded membrane voltages that are too hyperpolarized to permit Ca2+ channels entry.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Voltage-gated Ca2+ channels have been detected in the zona glomerulosa of the human adrenal, which suggests that Ca2+ channel blockers may directly influence the adrenocortical biosynthesis of aldosterone in vivo.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The amount of plasma renin secreted is an indirect function of the serum potassium as probably determined by sensors in the carotid artery.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), a pituitary peptide, also has some stimulating effect on aldosterone, probably by stimulating the formation of deoxycorticosterone, a precursor of aldosterone.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone is increased by blood loss, pregnancy, and possibly by further circumstances such as physical exertion, endotoxin shock, and burns.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The aldosterone production is also affected to one extent or another by nervous control, which integrates the inverse of carotid artery pressure, pain, posture, and probably emotion (anxiety, fear, and hostility) (including surgical stress).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Anxiety increases aldosterone, which must have evolved because of the time delay involved in migration of aldosterone into the cell nucleus.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Thus, there is an advantage to an animal's anticipating a future need from interaction with a predator, since too high a serum content of potassium has very adverse effects on nervous transmission.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Pressure-sensitive baroreceptors are found in the vessel walls of nearly all large arteries in the thorax and neck, but are particularly plentiful in the sinuses of the carotid arteries and in the arch of the aorta.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] These specialized receptors are sensitive to changes in mean arterial pressure.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] An increase in sensed pressure results in an increased rate of firing by the baroreceptors and a negative feedback response, lowering systemic arterial pressure.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone release causes sodium and water retention, which causes increased blood volume, and a subsequent increase in blood pressure, which is sensed by the baroreceptors.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] To maintain normal homeostasis these receptors also detect low blood pressure or low blood volume, causing aldosterone to be released.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] This results in sodium retention in the kidney, leading to water retention and increased blood volume.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone levels vary as an inverse function of sodium intake as sensed via osmotic pressure.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The slope of the response of aldosterone to serum potassium is almost independent of sodium intake.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Aldosterone is increased at low sodium intakes, but the rate of increase of plasma aldosterone as potassium rises in the serum is not much lower at high sodium intakes than it is at low.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Thus, potassium is strongly regulated at all sodium intakes by aldosterone when the supply of potassium is adequate, which it usually is in hunter-gatherer diets.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Feedback by aldosterone concentration itself is of a nonmorphological character (that is, other than changes in the cells' number or structure) and is poor, so the electrolyte feedbacks predominate, short term.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Hyperaldosteronism is abnormally increased levels of aldosterone, while hypoaldosteronism is abnormally decreased levels of aldosterone.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] A measurement of aldosterone in blood may be termed a *plasma aldosterone concentration* (*PAC*), which may be compared to plasma renin activity (PRA) as an aldosterone-to-renin ratio.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Primary aldosteronism, also known as *primary hyperaldosteronism*, is characterized by the overproduction of aldosterone by the adrenal glands, when not a result of excessive renin secretion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] It leads to arterial hypertension (high blood pressure) associated with hypokalemia, usually a diagnostic clue.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Secondary hyperaldosteronism, on the other hand, is due to overactivity of the renin–angiotensin system.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Conn's syndrome is primary hyperaldosteronism caused by an aldosterone-producing adenoma.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Depending on cause and other factors, hyperaldosteronism can be treated by surgery and/or medically, such as by aldosterone antagonists.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The ratio of renin to aldosterone is an effective screening test to screen for primary hyperaldosteronism related to adrenal adenomas.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] It is the most sensitive serum blood test to differentiate primary from secondary causes of hyperaldosteronism.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Blood obtained when the patient has been standing for more than 2 hours are more sensitive than those from when the patient is lying down.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] Before the test, individuals should not restrict salt and low potassium should be corrected before the test because it can suppress aldosterone secretion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] An ACTH stimulation test for aldosterone can help in determining the cause of hypoaldosteronism, with a low aldosterone response indicating a primary hypoaldosteronism of the adrenals, while a large response indicating a secondary hypoaldosteronism.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aldosterone] The most common cause of this condition (and related symptoms) is Addison's disease; it is typically treated by fludrocortisone, which has a much longer persistence (1 day) in the bloodstream.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] In organic chemistry, an **amide**, also known as an **organic amide** or a **carboxamide**, is a compound with the general formula R−C(=O)−NR′R″, where R, R', and R″ represent any group, typically organyl groups or hydrogen atoms.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The amide functional group plays an important role in the chemistry of life where, as peptide bonds, they link amino acids together to form proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides can be viewed as a derivative of a carboxylic acid (R−C(=O)−OH) with the hydroxyl group (−OH) replaced by an amino group (−NR′R″); or, equivalently, an acyl (alkanoyl) group (R−C(=O)−) joined to an amino group.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides are qualified as primary, secondary, and tertiary according to the number of acyl groups bounded to the nitrogen atom.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The core −C(=O)−(N) of amides is called the **amide group** (specifically, **carboxamide group**).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] In the usual nomenclature, one adds the term "amide" to the stem of the parent acid's name.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] For instance, the amide derived from acetic acid is named acetamide (CH3CONH2).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] IUPAC recommends ethanamide, but this and related formal names are rarely encountered.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] When the amide is derived from a primary or secondary amine, the substituents on nitrogen are indicated first in the name.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Thus, the amide formed from dimethylamine and acetic acid is *N*,*N*-dimethylacetamide (CH3CONMe2, where Me = CH3).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Usually even this name is simplified to dimethylacetamide.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Cyclic amides are called lactams; they are necessarily secondary or tertiary amides.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides are pervasive in nature and technology.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Proteins and important plastics like nylons, aramids, Twaron, and Kevlar are polymers whose units are connected by amide groups (polyamides); these linkages are easily formed, confer structural rigidity, and resist hydrolysis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides include many other important biological compounds, as well as many drugs like paracetamol, penicillin and LSD.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Low-molecular-weight amides, such as dimethylformamide, are common solvents.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The lone pair of electrons on the nitrogen atom is delocalized into the Carbonyl group, thus forming a partial double bond between nitrogen and carbon.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] In fact the O, C and N atoms have molecular orbitals occupied by delocalized electrons, forming a conjugated system.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Consequently, the three bonds of the nitrogen in amides is not pyramidal (as in the amines) but planar.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] This planar restriction prevents rotations about the N linkage and thus has important consequences for the mechanical properties of bulk material of such molecules, and also for the configurational properties of macromolecules built by such bonds.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The inability to rotate distinguishes amide groups from ester groups which allow rotation and results in a more flexible bulk material.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The C=O distance is shorter than the C-N distance by almost 10%.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The structure of an amide can be described also as a resonance between two alternative structures: neutral (A) and zwitterionic (B).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] It is estimated that for acetamide, structure A makes a 62% contribution to the structure, while structure B makes a 28% contribution (these figures do not sum to 100% because there are additional less-important resonance forms that are not depicted above).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Resonance is largely prevented in the very strained quinuclidone.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] In their IR spectra, amides exhibit a moderately intense *ν*CO band near 1650 cm−1.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The energy of this band is about 60 cm−1 lower than for the *ν*CO of esters and ketones.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] This difference reflects the contribution of the zwitterionic resonance structure.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Compared to amines, amides are very weak bases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] While the conjugate acid of an amine has a p*K*a of about 9.5, the conjugate acid of an amide has a p*K*a around −0.5.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Therefore, compared to amines, amides do not have acid–base properties that are as noticeable in water.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] This relative lack of basicity is explained by the withdrawing of electrons from the amine by the carbonyl.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] On the other hand, amides are much stronger bases than carboxylic acids, esters, aldehydes, and ketones (their conjugate acids' p*K*as are between −6 and −10).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The proton of a primary or secondary amide does not dissociate readily; its p*K*a is usually well above 15.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Conversely, under extremely acidic conditions, the carbonyl oxygen can become protonated with a p*K*a of roughly −1.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] It is not only because of the positive charge on the nitrogen but also because of the negative charge on the oxygen gained through resonance.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Because of the greater electronegativity of oxygen than nitrogen, the carbonyl (C=O) is a stronger dipole than the N–C dipole.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The presence of a C=O dipole and, to a lesser extent a N–C dipole, allows amides to act as H-bond acceptors.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] In primary and secondary amides, the presence of N–H dipoles allows amides to function as H-bond donors as well.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Thus amides can participate in hydrogen bonding with water and other protic solvents; the oxygen atom can accept hydrogen bonds from water and the N–H hydrogen atoms can donate H-bonds.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] As a result of interactions such as these, the water solubility of amides is greater than that of corresponding hydrocarbons.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] These hydrogen bonds also have an important role in the secondary structure of proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The solubilities of amides and esters are roughly comparable.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Typically amides are less soluble than comparable amines and carboxylic acids since these compounds can both donate and accept hydrogen bonds.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Tertiary amides, with the important exception of *N*,*N*-dimethylformamide, exhibit low solubility in water.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides do not readily participate in nucleophilic substitution reactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides are stable to water, and are roughly 100 times more stable towards hydrolysis than esters.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides can, however, be hydrolyzed to carboxylic acids in the presence of acid or base.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The stability of amide bonds has biological implications, since the amino acids that make up proteins are linked with amide bonds.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amide bonds are resistant enough to hydrolysis to maintain protein structure in aqueous environments but are susceptible to catalyzed hydrolysis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Primary and secondary amides do not react usefully with carbon nucleophiles.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Instead, Grignard reagents and organolithiums deprotonate an amide N-H bond.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Tertiary amides do not experience this problem, and react with carbon nucleophiles to give ketones; the amide anion (NR2−) is a very strong base and thus a very poor leaving group, so nucleophilic attack only occurs once.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] When reacted with carbon nucleophiles, *N*,*N*-dimethylformamide (DMF) can be used to introduce a formyl group.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Here, phenyllithium **1** attacks the carbonyl group of DMF **2**, giving tetrahedral intermediate **3**.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Because the dimethylamide anion is a poor leaving group, the intermediate does not collapse and another nucleophilic addition does not occur.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Upon acidic workup, the alkoxide is protonated to give **4**, then the amine is protonated to give **5**.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Elimination of a neutral molecule of dimethylamine and loss of a proton give benzaldehyde, **6**.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] A new class of amide reactions was discovered in 2015 by the research teams of Neil Garg and Ken Houk, showing that amides can be converted to esters using nickel catalysis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The nickel catalyst breaks the ordinarily strong amide C-N bond through oxidative addition.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Many other amide cross-couplings were subsequently developed using nickel or palladium catalysis, including Suzuki-Miyaura couplings, allowing for amides to be readily converted to numerous other functional groups.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides hydrolyse in hot alkali as well as in strong acidic conditions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Acidic conditions yield the carboxylic acid and the ammonium ion while basic hydrolysis yield the carboxylate ion and ammonia.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The protonation of the initially generated amine under acidic conditions and the deprotonation of the initially generated carboxylic acid under basic conditions render these processes non-catalytic and irreversible.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Electrophiles other than protons react with the carbonyl oxygen.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] This step often precedes hydrolysis, which is catalyzed by both Brønsted acids and Lewis acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Peptidase enzymes and some synthetic catalysts often operate by attachment of electrophiles to the carbonyl oxygen.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Amides are usually prepared by coupling a carboxylic acid with an amine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Esters are far superior substrates relative to carboxylic acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Peptide synthesis use coupling agents such as HATU, HOBt, or PyBOP.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] The hydrolysis of nitriles is conducted on an industrial scale to produce fatty amides.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Laboratory procedures are also available.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] Many specialized methods also yield amides.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amide] A variety of reagents, e.g. tris(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl) borate have been developed for specialized applications.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] PAH is useful for the measurement of renal plasma flow.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] The renal extraction ratio of PAH in a normal individual is approximately 0.92.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] This means that unlike inulin and creatinine, which are filtered in the glomerulus and ignored by the rest of the kidney, aminohippuric acid is both filtered and secreted, being almost entirely removed from the bloodstream in a normal kidney.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] Aminohippuric acid is often used as the sodium salt sodium *para*-aminohippurate.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] During World War II, *para*-aminohippurate was given along with penicillin in order to prolong the time penicillin circulated in the blood.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] Because both penicillin and *para*-aminohippurate compete for the same transporter in the kidney, administering *para*-aminohippurate with penicillin decreased the clearance of penicillin from the body by the kidney, providing better antibacterial therapy.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/aminohippuric-acid] Transporters found in the kidney eliminate organic anions and cations from the blood by moving substances, in this case, drug metabolites, from blood into urine.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The **Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical** (**ATC**) **Classification System** is a drug classification system that classifies the active ingredients of drugs according to the organ or system on which they act and their therapeutic, pharmacological and chemical properties.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its purpose is an aid to monitor drug use and for research to improve quality medication use.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It does not imply drug recommendation or efficacy.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It is controlled by the World Health Organization Collaborating Centre for Drug Statistics Methodology (WHOCC), and was first published in 1976.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This pharmaceutical coding system divides drugs into different groups according to the organ or system on which they act, their therapeutic intent or nature, and the drug's chemical characteristics.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Different brands share the same code if they have the same active substance and indications.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Each bottom-level ATC code stands for a pharmaceutically used substance, or a combination of substances, in a single indication (or use).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC classification system is a strict hierarchy, meaning that each code necessarily has one and only one parent code, except for the 14 codes at the topmost level which have no parents.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The codes are semantic identifiers, meaning they depict information by themselves beyond serving as identifiers (namely, the codes depict themselves the complete lineage of parenthood).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] As of 7 May 2020, there are 6,331 codes in ATC; the table below gives the count per level.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system is based on the earlier Anatomical Classification System, which is intended as a tool for the pharmaceutical industry to classify pharmaceutical products (as opposed to their active ingredients).
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This system, confusingly also called ATC, was initiated in 1971 by the European Pharmaceutical Market Research Association (EphMRA) and is being maintained by the EphMRA and Intellus.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its codes are organised into four levels.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The WHO's system, having five levels, is an extension and modification of the EphMRA's.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The first level of the code indicates the anatomical main group and consists of one letter.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The second level of the code indicates the therapeutic subgroup and consists of two digits.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The third level of the code indicates the therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fourth level of the code indicates the chemical/therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fifth level of the code indicates the chemical substance and consists of two digits.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The *Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical Classification System for veterinary medicinal products* (ATCvet) is used to classify veterinary drugs.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATCvet codes can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the ATC code of most human medications.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] For example, furosemide for veterinary use has the code **Q**C03CA01.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Some codes are used exclusively for veterinary drugs, such as *QI Immunologicals*, *QJ51 Antibacterials for intramammary use* or *QN05AX90 amperozide*.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Herbal ATC system (HATC) is an ATC classification of herbal substances; it differs from the regular ATC system by using 4 digits instead of 2 at the 5th level group.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The herbal classification is not adopted by WHO.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Uppsala Monitoring Centre is responsible for the Herbal ATC classification, and it is part of the WHODrug Global portfolio available by subscription.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system also includes defined daily doses (DDDs) for many drugs.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This is a measurement of drug consumption based on the usual daily dose for a given drug.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] National issues of the ATC classification, such as the German *Anatomisch-therapeutisch-chemische Klassifikation mit Tagesdosen*, may include additional codes and DDDs not present in the WHO version.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC follows guidelines in creating new codes for newly approved drugs.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An application is submitted to WHO for ATC classification and DDD assignment.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] A preliminary or temporary code is assigned and published on the website and in the *WHO Drug Information* for comment or objection.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] New ATC/DDD codes are discussed at the semi-annual Working Group meeting.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] If accepted it becomes a final decision and published semi-annually on the website and *WHO Drug Information* and implemented in the annual print/on-line ACT/DDD Index on January 1.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Changes to existing ATC/DDD follow a similar process to become temporary codes and if accepted become a final decision as ATC/DDD alterations.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC and DDD alterations are only valid and implemented in the coming annual updates; the original codes must continue until the end of the year.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An updated version of the complete on-line/print ATC index with DDDs is published annually on January 1.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/atc-code-v04] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QV04**.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/atc-code-v04] ATCvet codes without corresponding human ATC codes are cited with the leading Q in the following list.
[src:aminohippuric-acid/atc-code-v04] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
